# Freshness Detection of Fruits and Vegetables
I want to make freshness detection of fruits and vegetables in which I want the user to scan the fruits and vegetables and user gets the following details of the furit/vegetable
- Freshness percentage
- How many days will the fruit/vegetable be healthy or fresh or goof to use and eat
- The Calories it contain
- Benefit of having that item
- With and without refrigerator how long its usable

# What the user will get (final product features)
When a user scans a fruit/vegetable (photo or live camera), the app returns:
-Detected item (name + confidence)
-Mentioning on what basis it's predicted item's freshness
-Freshness percentage (0–100%) with explanation (visual heatmap of regions affecting the decision)
-Estimated usable days (how many days it will remain good to eat)
-Without refrigerator (ambient conditions)
-With refrigerator (typical fridge conditions)
-Calories (estimated per whole item or per user-selected weight/portion)
-Benefits / Nutrition highlights (short bullet list: vitamins, fiber, key health benefits)
-Action suggestion (use now / use within X days / cook / freeze / discard)
-Confidence & uncertainty (probability + why — e.g., lighting poor, occluded)
-Optional: time-series freshness prediction (graph), storage tips, recipe suggestions according to Indian Cuisine

# UX / UI flow (simple & clear)
Launch camera → auto-detect bounding box around item → user taps “Scan”
Progress states: analyzing (small spinner) → result card appears
Result card layout:

-Top: detected item & confidence
-Big freshness gauge (0–100%)
-Two columns: Days usable (no fridge / fridge)
-Calories + portion selector dropdown
-Benefits (3–5 bullets)
-“Why this result” (small expandable: Grad-CAM heatmap + short text)
-Buttons: Save log / Use-recipe / Share / Retake

